-- China shares snap 3 weeks of gains, banks drag
-- By Grace Li
-- Fri Jun 06, 2014 03:06AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 6 (Reuters) - China shares posted their first weekly loss in four, as investors pulled money out of the market while awaiting direction from major economic data in the coming week.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> ended down 0.5 percent at 2,029.96 points. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings shed 0.7 percent. On the week, the SSEC lost 0.5 percent, while the CSI300 was down 1 percent.  Mid-sized banks were the key underperformers on Friday. China Merchants Bank <600036.SS> slid 1.6 percent, Industrial Bank <601166.SS> sank 1.2 percent, and China Minsheng Banking Corp <600016.SS> fell 0.8 percent. Index heavyweight China Vanke <000002.SZ>, China's largest property developer by market value, ended down 0.7 percent.